1. Get just the IP directly:
podman inspect -f '{{ .NetworkSettings.IPAddress }}' <container_id_or_name>

2. If the container is in a user-defined network:
podman inspect -f '{{ .NetworkSettings.Networks.bridge.IPAddress }}' <container_id_or_name>

3. For more details (full JSON output):

podman inspect <container_id_or_name>

…and look under .NetworkSettings



podman port <container_id_or_name>




1. Using podman ps -q with inspect:
podman ps -q | xargs -n1 podman inspect -f '{{ .Name }}: {{ .NetworkSettings.IPAddress }}'

This will list each container’s name and IP.
2. If containers are in a user-defined network (bridge, etc.):
podman ps -q | xargs -n1 podman inspect -f '{{ .Name }}: {{ range .NetworkSettings.Networks }}{{ .IPAddress }}{{ end }}'

3. If you just want the raw IPs:
podman ps -q | xargs -n1 podman inspect -f '{{ .NetworkSettings.IPAddress }}'

⚠️ Reminder: if your containers are running with slirp4netns (the default rootless network), .NetworkSettings.IPAddress will usually be empty — you’ll need to check forwarded ports with:
podman port -a
